{"title_page": "White-throated earthcreeper", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = White-throated earthcreeper\n| image =  Upucerthia albigula -Peru-8.jpg\n| caption =\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22702068/0 |title=''Upucerthia albigula'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Upucerthia\n| species = albigula\n| authority = [[Carl Eduard Hellmayr|Hellmayr]], 1932\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''white-throated earthcreeper''' (''Upucerthia albigula'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Furnariidae]].\nIt is found in [[Chile]] and [[Peru]].\nIts natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical high-altitude [[shrubland]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q432191}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:earthcreeper, white-throated}}\n[[Category:Upucerthia|white-throated earthcreeper]]\n[[Category:Birds of Chile]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Peruvian Andes]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1932|white-throated earthcreeper]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Furnariidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = White-throated earthcreeper\n| image =  Upucerthia albigula -Peru-8.jpg\n| caption =\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22702068/0 |title=''Upucerthia albigula'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Upucerthia\n| species = albigula\n| authority = [[Carl Eduard Hellmayr|Hellmayr]], 1932\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''white-throated earthcreeper''' (''Upucerthia albigula'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Furnariidae]] family.\nIt is found in [[Chile]] and [[Peru]].\nIts natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical high-altitude [[shrubland]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q432191}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:earthcreeper, white-throated}}\n[[Category:Upucerthia|white-throated earthcreeper]]\n[[Category:Birds of Chile]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Peruvian Andes]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1932|white-throated earthcreeper]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Furnariidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White-throated_earthcreeper"}
{"title_page": "Daniela Rossell", "text_new": "{{More citations needed}}\n{{Expand with relevant sources}}\n{{Further reading cleanup}}\n\n'''Daniela Rossell''' (born 1973, [[Mexico City]])<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/daniela-rossell-6237|title=Daniela Rossell|last=|first=|date=|website=Tate Museum|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] photographer best known for her portraits of the privileged Mexican elite,<ref name=\":0\" /> of which she herself is a member. Her best-known photographic work was published in 2002 under the title ''Ricas y Famosas'',<ref name=\":3\" /> which is a photographic series portraying upper-class Mexican women, many whom had connections to the PRI [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumhue.com/blog/2018/12/6/5-fast-facts-daniela-rossell|title=5 Fast Facts: Daniela Rossell|website=Museum Hue|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>  \n\n== Life ==\nRossell was born into the elite class she would later photograph. She is the granddaughter of two former Mexican governors.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Her mother was an art collector, and Rossell was raised with an appreciation for fine art.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://nmwa.org/explore/artist-profiles/daniela-rossell|title=Artist Profiles: Daniela Rosell, National Museum of Women in the Arts}}</ref> She was educated at the [[American School Foundation]], an exclusive and academically rigorous prep school in Mexico City.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation}} There, she developed an interest in theatre and began acting at age sixteen. She then briefly studied painting at the National School of Visual Arts, but left to pursue a career in photography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumhue.com/blog/2018/12/6/5-fast-facts-daniela-rossell|title=5 Fast Facts: Daniela Rossell, Museum Hue}}</ref> \n\nRossell currently lives and works in Mexico City<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenenaftaligallery.com/artists/daniela-rossell/biography1|title=Artist Bio, Greene Naftali Gallery}}</ref> and shows throughout [[Latin America]], [[Europe]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfmoma.org/explore/multimedia/videos/487|title=San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Art ==\nThe photographic series Daniela Rossell is best known for is ''Ricas y Famosas'' (Rich and Famous),<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/reviews/200004/daniela-rossell-354|title=Nico Israel on Daniela Rossell|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> which spanned over the years 1994-2001 and was published as a book in 2009. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation and an ISBN}}\n\nThe first models for these photographs were as friends and family of the artist, who were Mexican elite, and then began to spread to other elite women who volunteered to model. Each model chooses how to depict their identity surrounded by their lavish material items and selling sex appeal in their poses. Rossell believes that her models are influenced by magazines and television shows in how they should perform in front of the camera because they want to look American.<ref name=\"SFMOMA Rossell\">{{cite web|title=Daniela Rossell on Her Book Ricas y Famosas|url=http://www.sfmoma.org/explore/multimedia/videos/487|website=SFMOMA|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> This quest to look American requires these models to modify their lifestyle and manipulation of identity that is a form of unhappiness.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation or is this WP:OPINION}} Despite having materialistically everything, these women struggle to find satisfaction in who they are because of the fantasy portrayed of America. When looking at the photographs is the large amounts of art and non-Christian icons mixed with Christian art found in these lavish homes. For example, one woman is posed lying seductively across a massive sized Buddha surrounded by champagne and money. The juxtaposition between sacred object and sexual attraction makes for a conflicting yet entertaining subject.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation}}\n\nOne of the themes of the series is femininity and the role of women. The artist describes the home as the territory of the women, and by taking pictures of women within their own homes we are granted a glimpse into this constructed world.<ref name=\"SFMOMA Rossell Femininity\">{{cite web|title=Daniela Rossell on Femininity|url=http://www.sfmoma.org/explore/multimedia/videos/488|website=SFMOMA|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> For example, one of the subjects surrounds herself with self-portraits and includes her personal waiter in the scene, putting on display that this is a space dedicated to her. In these highly cluttered environments the female models blend in with the lavish objects and Rossell uses this composition to reemphasize the objectifying of women in photographs.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation or WP:OPINION}} Often seen in fashion and commercial advertising campaigns the women photographed become synonymous with the object being sold..{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation or WP:OPINION}}\n\nAnother theme that is found in the series is Mexican history and identity. Rather than depicting the romanticized views of the Mexican villages or the harsh images of the urban poor, Rossell depicts the wealthy minority. Rossell herself  is a part of this demographic and in turn this is the Mexican history she relates to. Also, the elite lives of her subjects were unknown to the rest of Mexico, her photographs also serve as social and political documents. After the release of  her book ''Ricas y Famosas'', the people who originally had been eager to model were angry with the artist.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal|last1=Thompson|first1=Ginger|title=The Rich, Famous and Aghast: A Peep Show|journal=The New York Times|date=September 25, 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/25/international/americas/25MEXI.html|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> The public praised Rossell for her cinematic eye and ability to create provocative photos showing that flashy lifestyles are visible in all cultures.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cotter|first1=Holland|title=Art in Review; Daniela Rossell|journal=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/arts/art-in-review-daniela-rossell.html|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn writing about Rossell's portraits of the Mexican elite, [[Slate (magazine)|''Slate Magazine'']] observed:<blockquote>The narrative of Mexico as our impoverished and drug cartel\u2013ridden neighbor dominates most news coverage in America, but that\u2019s only one part of a large and diverse country. Photographer Daniela Rossell brings us tales of the polar opposite segment of Mexican society with her series ''Ricas y Famosas'', which depicts the children of Mexico\u2019s most privileged class of society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2012/12/daniela-rossell-documenting-the-rich-and-famous-mexican-youth-photos.html|title=The Poor Little Rich Girls of Mexico|last=Coppelman|first=Alyssa|date=2012-12-11|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref></blockquote>In discussing the same series of photographs, [[The New York Times|''The New York Times'']] wrote:<blockquote><nowiki>''</nowiki>Ricas y Famosas,<nowiki>''</nowiki> a book of 89 photographs, is not an exercise in kitsch fantasy. Part Town and Country, part Playboy, the book exposes the decadent, some say depraved, lifestyles of Mexico's wealthy elite -- or, as the title would have it, the rich and famous.<ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nHer photographs have been exhibited worldwide, most notably at:\n\n[[Tate Modern]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[National Museum of Women in the Arts|The National Museum of Women in the Arts]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[MoMA PS1]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinamericanart.com/en/artists/daniela-rossell/biography.html|title=Latin American Art|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Kunsthallen Nikolaj]], Copenhagen Contemporary Art Center, [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://art.stanford.edu/events/studio-lecture-series-daniela-rossell|title=Studio Lecture Series: Daniela Rossell {{!}} Department of Art & Art History|website=art.stanford.edu|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UxlxDJ_FRLs Interview video with Daniela Rossell]{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rossell, Daniela}}\n[[Category:Mexican photographers]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican women photographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed}}\n{{Expand with relevant sources}}\n{{Further reading cleanup}}\n\n'''Daniela Rossell''' (born 1973, [[Mexico City]])<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tate.org.uk/art/artists/daniela-rossell-6237|title=Daniela Rossell|last=|first=|date=|website=Tate Museum|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] photographer best known for her portraits of the privileged Mexican elite,<ref name=\":0\" /> of which she herself is a member. Her best-known photographic work was published in 2002 under the title ''Ricas y Famosas'',<ref name=\":3\" /> which is a photographic series portraying upper-class Mexican women, many whom had connections to the PRI [[Institutional Revolutionary Party]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumhue.com/blog/2018/12/6/5-fast-facts-daniela-rossell|title=5 Fast Facts: Daniela Rossell|website=Museum Hue|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>  \n\n== Life ==\nRossell was born into the elite class she would later photograph. She is the granddaughter of two former Mexican governors.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Her mother was an art collector, and Rossell was raised with an appreciation for fine art.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://nmwa.org/explore/artist-profiles/daniela-rossell|title=Artist Profiles: Daniela Rosell, National Museum of Women in the Arts}}</ref> She was educated at the [[American School Foundation]], an exclusive and academically rigorous prep school in Mexico City.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation}} There, she developed an interest in theatre and began acting at age sixteen. She then briefly studied painting at the National School of Visual Arts, but left to pursue a career in photography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.museumhue.com/blog/2018/12/6/5-fast-facts-daniela-rossell|title=5 Fast Facts: Daniela Rossell, Museum Hue}}</ref> \n\nRossell currently lives and works in Mexico City<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greenenaftaligallery.com/artists/daniela-rossell/biography1|title=Artist Bio, Greene Naftali Gallery}}</ref> and shows throughout [[Latin America]], [[Europe]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfmoma.org/explore/multimedia/videos/487|title=San Francisco Museum of Modern Art|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Art ==\nThe photographic series Daniela Rossell is best known for is ''Ricas y Famosas'' (Rich and Famous),<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/print/reviews/200004/daniela-rossell-354|title=Nico Israel on Daniela Rossell|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> which spanned over the years 1994-2001 and was published as a book in 2009. {{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation and an ISBN}}\n\nThe first models for these photographs were as friends and family of the artist, who were Mexican elite, and then began to spread to other elite women who volunteered to model. Each model chooses how to depict their identity surrounded by their lavish material items and selling sex appeal in their poses. Rossell believes that her models are influenced by magazines and television shows in how they should perform in front of the camera because they want to look American.<ref name=\"SFMOMA Rossell\">{{cite web|title=Daniela Rossell on Her Book Ricas y Famosas|url=http://www.sfmoma.org/explore/multimedia/videos/487|website=SFMOMA|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> This quest to look American requires these models to modify their lifestyle and manipulation of identity that is a form of unhappiness.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation or is this WP:OPINION}} Despite having materialistically everything, these women struggle to find satisfaction in who they are because of the fantasy portrayed of America. When looking at the photographs is the large amounts of art and non-Christian icons mixed with Christian art found in these lavish homes. For example, one woman is posed lying seductively across a massive sized Buddha surrounded by champagne and money. The juxtaposition between sacred object and sexual attraction makes for a conflicting yet entertaining subject.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation}}\n\nOne of the themes of the series is femininity and the role of women. The artist describes the home as the territory of the women, and by taking pictures of women within their own homes we are granted a glimpse into this constructed world.<ref name=\"SFMOMA Rossell Femininity\">{{cite web|title=Daniela Rossell on Femininity|url=http://www.sfmoma.org/explore/multimedia/videos/488|website=SFMOMA|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> For example, one of the subjects surrounds herself with self-portraits and includes her personal waiter in the scene, putting on display that this is a space dedicated to her. In these highly cluttered environments the female models blend in with the lavish objects and Rossell uses this composition to reemphasize the objectifying of women in photographs.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation or WP:OPINION}} Often seen in fashion and commercial advertising campaigns the women photographed become synonymous with the object being sold..{{Citation needed|date=April 2020|reason=This requires a citation or WP:OPINION}}\n\nAnother theme that is found in the series is Mexican history and identity. Rather than depicting the romanticized views of the Mexican villages or the harsh images of the urban poor, Rossell depicts the wealthy minority. Rossell herself  is a part of this demographic and in turn this is the Mexican history she relates to. Also, the elite lives of her subjects were unknown to the rest of Mexico, her photographs also serve as social and political documents. After the release of  her book ''Ricas y Famosas'', the people who originally had been eager to model were angry with the artist.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal|last1=Thompson|first1=Ginger|title=The Rich, Famous and Aghast: A Peep Show|journal=The New York Times|date=September 25, 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/25/international/americas/25MEXI.html|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> The public praised Rossell for her cinematic eye and ability to create provocative photos showing that flashy lifestyles are visible in all cultures.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cotter|first1=Holland|title=Art in Review; Daniela Rossell|journal=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2002|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/arts/art-in-review-daniela-rossell.html|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nIn writing about Rossell's portraits of the Mexican elite, [[Slate (magazine)|''Slate Magazine'']] observed:<blockquote>The narrative of Mexico as our impoverished and drug cartel\u2013ridden neighbor dominates most news coverage in America, but that\u2019s only one part of a large and diverse country. Photographer Daniela Rossell brings us tales of the polar opposite segment of Mexican society with her series ''Ricas y Famosas'', which depicts the children of Mexico\u2019s most privileged class of society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2012/12/daniela-rossell-documenting-the-rich-and-famous-mexican-youth-photos.html|title=The Poor Little Rich Girls of Mexico|last=Coppelman|first=Alyssa|date=2012-12-11|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref></blockquote>In discussing the same series of photographs, [[The New York Times|''The New York Times'']] wrote:<blockquote><nowiki>''</nowiki>Ricas y Famosas,<nowiki>''</nowiki> a book of 89 photographs, is not an exercise in kitsch fantasy. Part Town and Country, part Playboy, the book exposes the decadent, some say depraved, lifestyles of Mexico's wealthy elite -- or, as the title would have it, the rich and famous.<ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nHer photographs have been exhibited worldwide, most notably at:\n\n[[Tate Modern]], [[London]], [[United Kingdom|UK]]<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[National Museum of Women in the Arts|The National Museum of Women in the Arts]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington, DC]]<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n[[MoMA PS1]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latinamericanart.com/en/artists/daniela-rossell/biography.html|title=Latin American Art|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UxlxDJ_FRLs Interview video with Daniela Rossell]{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rossell, Daniela}}\n[[Category:Mexican photographers]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican women photographers]]\n", "name_user": "Soydeaguadilla", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExhibitions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniela_Rossell"}
{"title_page": "White-winged cinclodes", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = White-winged cinclodes\n| image = Cinclodes atacamensis White-winged Cinclodes.JPG\n| image_caption = White-winged cinclodes at [[San Pedro de Atacama]], [[Antofagasta Region]], [[Chile]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22702114/0 |title=''Cinclodes atacamensis'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cinclodes\n| species = atacamensis\n| authority = ([[Rodolfo Amando Philippi|Philippi]], 1857)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''white-winged cinclodes''' (''Cinclodes atacamensis'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Furnariidae]].\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical high-altitude [[grassland]] and [[river]]s.\n\n== Subspecies ==\n* ''Cinclodes atacamensis atacamensis'': [[Puna grassland]] ;\n* ''C. a. schocolatinus'': [[Sierras de C\u00f3rdoba]] and northeastern San Luis.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1261575}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:cinclodes, white-winged}}\n[[Category:Cinclodes|white-winged cinclodes]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Puna grassland]]\n[[Category:Birds of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1857|white-winged cinclodes]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Furnariidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = White-winged cinclodes\n| image = Cinclodes atacamensis White-winged Cinclodes.JPG\n| image_caption = White-winged cinclodes at [[San Pedro de Atacama]], [[Antofagasta Region]], [[Chile]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22702114/0 |title=''Cinclodes atacamensis'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Cinclodes\n| species = atacamensis\n| authority = ([[Rodolfo Amando Philippi|Philippi]], 1857)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''white-winged cinclodes''' (''Cinclodes atacamensis'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Furnariidae]] family.\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical high-altitude [[grassland]] and [[river]]s.\n\n== Subspecies ==\n* ''Cinclodes atacamensis atacamensis'': [[Puna grassland]] ;\n* ''C. a. schocolatinus'': [[Sierras de C\u00f3rdoba]] and northeastern San Luis.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1261575}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:cinclodes, white-winged}}\n[[Category:Cinclodes|white-winged cinclodes]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Puna grassland]]\n[[Category:Birds of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1857|white-winged cinclodes]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Furnariidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White-winged_cinclodes"}
